===Noun===
{{en-noun|~|mercuries}}

# A [[metal]].
## A [[silvery]]-colored, toxic, [[metallic]] chemical element, [[liquid]] at room temperature, with atomic number 80 and symbol [[Hg]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
##: {{synonyms|en|azoth|q1=in alchemy|hydrargyrum|q2=in medical and sometimes chemical use|quicksilver|q3=not in technical use}}
## {{lb|en|science|historical}} One of the [[elemental]] principles formerly thought to be present in all [[metal]]s. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
## {{lb|en|with definite article}} Ambient pressure or temperature (''from the use of mercury in [[barometer]]s and [[thermometer]]s''). {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
##: {{ux|en|The '''mercury''' there has averaged 37.6°C, 2.3°C above the February norm.}}
## {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[liveliness|Liveliness]], [[volatility]]. {{defdate|17th-18th c.}}
##* {{rfdatek|en|Bishop Burnet}}
##*: He was so full of '''mercury''' that he could not fix long in any friendship, or to any design.
# Any of several types of [[plant#Noun|plant]].
## {{senseid|en|plant}} An annual plant, [[annual mercury]] (''[[Mercurialis annua]]''), formerly grown for its medicinal properties; {{vern|French mercury}}, {{vern|herb mercury}}. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
##: {{synonyms|en|mercurial}}
##* '''1653''', {{w|Nicholas Culpeper}}, ''The English Physician Enlarged'', Folio Society 2007, p. 188:
##*: Towards the tops of the stalks and branches come forth at every joint in the male '''Mercury''' two small round green heads, standing together upon a short footstalk, which growing ripe are the seeds, not having any flower.
## Any plant of any species of the genus and the genus ''[[Mercurialis]]''.
## A similar edible plant (''[[Blitum bonus-henricus]]''), otherwise known as [[English mercury]] or {{vern|allgood|novern=1}}. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
## {{lb|en|US|regional}} The [[poison oak]] or [[poison ivy]]. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}

